# API Design

## Read vs Mutate

| Operation | Entry point |
|-----------|-------------|
| Reads (GET, lists, health) | Route Handlers or Server Component queries |
| Mutations (create, update, workflows) | Server Actions |

Do not build REST CRUD endpoints per module. Only `auth`, `health`, and `cron` use Route Handlers for mutations.

## Response Envelope

```typescript
{
  success: boolean;
  data?: T;
  error?: { code: string; message: string };
  meta?: { page?: number; total?: number };
}
```

## HTTP Status Codes

| Situation | Code |
|-----------|------|
| Success (read/create) | 200, 201 |
| Validation error | 400 |
| Unauthorized | 401 |
| Forbidden | 403 |
| Not found | 404 |
| Conflict (constraint violation) | 409 |
| Server error | 500 |

Never return 200 with an error. Map `AppError` subclasses to the correct status code.

## Server Action Pattern

```typescript
export async function allocateAssetAction(input: unknown) {
  const session = await requireSession();
  const data = allocateAssetSchema.parse(input);
  const user = toSessionUser(session);
  await AllocationPolicy.assertCanAllocate(user, data.assetId);
  const result = await allocateAssetService.execute(user, data);
  return success(result);
}
```

No business logic in the action — validate, authorize, delegate, return envelope.
